twitter.text:
As promised.  https://t.co/Go0DbAxou7

v4 now supports TACACS+ as an experimental protocol.
FreeRADIUS defines yet another RADIUS standard.  https://t.co/pwzHphCtyd
Big news next week.  No v4, but some major new functionality in the v4.0.x branch.
v4 update.  Tested master / worker thread exchanging fake packets.  1M req/reply per second per thread.  The new network IO is scalable.
Preliminary support for LuaJit via rlm_lua in v4.0.x.  Should be MUCH faster than other interpreted languages.
The v4.0.x branch now supports sigtran for EAP-SIM.  i.e. SS7 integration.  Be warned, though, license issues apply!  Use at your own risk.
Much of the "back end" stays the same.  Modules, config files, unlang, etc.  The only work left to do now is the "front end" networking.
A good chunk of the version 4 implementation has already been done.  The unlang interpreter is now asynchronous.
Version 4 design notes on the Wiki.  https://t.co/LTP4oByNNw  Pictures and schematics uploaded next week.
Designing version 4.  Implementing version 4 from the ground up.  No memory copies.  Minimal system calls.  Goal 100K to 1M packets/s

rlm_python isn't always packaged depending on the distribution.

Basic build instructions can be found here: http://wiki.freeradius.org/building/Home

You will also need to have installed the python-dev/python-devel package on your system.  If python still doesn't work you may need to specify the path to the python binary manually by passing it to configure e.g. .

If you just wan to verify the configure scripts have picked up python 

On my system (macOS 10.11.6) the output when python is found is:



Once the configure script find the python binary, it'll generally all "just work", as it can then get compilation and linking flags from python itself.

Try some HTTP website like http://freeradius.org/.

commit.message: move proxy_state random number to main module
print out Proxy-State and Message-Authenticator when proxying
print reply packet VPs, and add to request VPs

create and use Session-State-User-Name

so that we can cache the User-Name in Session-State without
affecting the User-Name in the reply.

The default "send Access-Accept" policy adds all of the session-state
attributes to the reply.  Which in this case would mean User-Name...
but we don't want that.  i.e. we don't want our internal policies
to pollute whatever the user wants to send back
